\section*{MRI scanner components:}

MRI scanner is tunnel shaped machine composed of the following components:
1. Large magnet that produces a very strong magnetic field.
2. Radiofrequency coils which produce radiofrequency (RF) signals and receive them from the tissue, they are located within the magnet assembly and relatively close to the patient's body.
3. Gradient coils located within the main magnet, they are three different gradient coils, each one of these produce three different magnetic fields that are each less strong than the main field. The gradient coils create a variable field ( $\mathrm{x}, \mathrm{y}, \mathrm{z}$ ) that can be increased or decreased to allow specific and different parts of the body to be scanned by altering and adjusting the main magnetic field.
4. Patient Table that slides the patient into the MRI machine.
5. Computer System whose major function is to receive, record, and analyze the images of the patient's body that have been scanned. The Computer System is composed of a very sensitive antenna that easily detects the RF signals emitted by the patient's body while undergoing examination and feeds this information in order to be interpreted to produce an understandable image of the body part being examined. (Figure 1.16)
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-024.jpg?height=748&width=900&top_left_y=963&top_left_x=371)

Figure 1.16 MRI machine

\section*{The Basic concept of MRI imaging:}

During the scan, the patient lies on a table that slides inside a tunnel-shaped machine. The position at which the patient lies down on the table is determined by the part of the body that is being scanned. Once the part of the body under examination is in the exact centre of the magnetic field, the scanning process is started (Figure 1.17).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-025.jpg?height=484&width=824&top_left_y=560&top_left_x=248)

Figure 1.17 MRI imaging
In normal circumstances, hydrogen protons of the human body spin on their own axis in a manner very similar to the planet earth, with a north-south pole (Figure 1.18). In this respect hydrogen protons behave like small bar magnets distributed in the body with their axes randomly aligned.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-025.jpg?height=296&width=837&top_left_y=1253&top_left_x=244)

Figure 1.18 Hydrogen protons spin on their own axis in a manner similar to the planet earth

To obtain an MR image of a human body, the following steps take place:
1. First, the human body is placed in a uniform magnetic field in the range between 0.5 to 1.5 Tesla. As a result, the human body's hydrogen protons will precess about the magnetic field direction like gyroscopes and line up, creating a magnetic vector along the axis of the magnetic field (Figure 1.19). This behavior is termed as Larmor precession; the frequency of Larmor precession is proportional to the applied magnetic field strength as defined by the Larmor frequency.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-026.jpg?height=703&width=661&top_left_y=626&top_left_x=495)

Figure 1.19 After magnetization, hydrogen nuclei align with the magnetic field and create a net magnetic moment parallel to the direction of the magnetic field
2. Next, a radio-frequency (RF) pulse with a frequency equal to the Larmor frequency is applied perpendicular to the direction of the magnetic field, causing hydrogen nuclei to gradually tilt perpendicular to the direction of the magnetic field as in (Figure 1.20). It has been found that there is specific time required for all hydrogen nuclie of each tissue to be organized in the perpendicular direction or transverse to the direction of the magnetic field; known as transverse relaxation timeT2.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-027.jpg?height=738&width=610&top_left_y=575&top_left_x=330)

Figure 1.20 The RF pulse causes the net magnetic moment of the nuclei to tilt perpendicular to the direction of the magnetic field
3. The third step when the Radiofrequency pulse stops, the nuclei realign themselves again parallel with the direction of the magnetic field. Returning to equilibrium is referred to as relaxation. During relaxation the nuclei lose energy by emitting their own RF signal (Figure 1.21). This signal is referred to as the free-induction decay (FID) response signal. The FID response signal is measured by a conductive field coil placed around the object being imaged. This measurement is processed or reconstructed to obtain 3D grey-scale MR images on the monitor.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-028.jpg?height=731&width=915&top_left_y=623&top_left_x=374)

Figure 1.21 When the RF pulse stops, the nuclei return to equilibrium again parallel with the direction of the magnetic field, during realignment, the nuclei lose energy and a measurable RF signal is processed to obtain 3D grey-scale MR images on the monitor.

Time required for all hydrogen nuclei of each tissue to return to equilibrium again parallel with the direction of the magnetic field and to be organized in this direction is known as longitudinal relaxation timeT1.

According to the strength of the bond between hydrogen nuclei of different types of tissues, there are four types of tissues:
1. Fluids: the strength of the bond between hydrogen nuclei of fluids is not very strong and not very weak, allowing them to move freely.
2. Fats: the strength of the bond between hydrogen nuclei of fats is similar to fluids, allowing them also to move freely.
3. Solids: the liking bond between hydrogen nuclei of solids is very strong, which does not allow them to move freely.
4. Gasses: there no bond liking between hydrogen nuclei of gasses.

\section*{MRI image display:}

There are many types of MR images their display depends on many factors:
1. T1 weighted MR Image: in this type of image, displayed tissue contrast depends on the longitudinal relaxation time hydrogen nuclei of each tissue. According to tissue characteristics, solids and gasses haven't got relaxation time, because the bond between hydrogen nuclei of solids is very strong and there no bond liking between hydrogen nuclei of gasses, there for solids and gasses appear dark in T1 weight image, while fats have short relaxation time because quickly realigns its longitudinal magnetization therefore appears bright on a T1 weighted image. Conversely, fluids has much slower longitudinal magnetization realignment after RF pulse, therefore it has less transverse magnetization after an RF pulse. Thus, fluids has low signal and appears dark (Figure 1.22).
2. T2 weighted MR Image: this type of image depends on the transverse relaxation time of hydrogen nuclei of each tissue after application of the RF pulse, as mentioned above, solids and gasses haven't got relaxation time and consequently they haven't got transverse relaxation time, so solids and gasses appear dark in T2 weight image, because transverse relaxation basically depends on the net magnetization vector and the radiofrequency pulse, fats and fluids appear bright in T 2 weighted image(Figure 1.23).
3. Proton density weighted MR image: The voxel intensity of this type of MR image displayed on MR monitor of a specific tissue type depends on the proton density of the tissue; the higher the proton density, the stronger the FID response signal, Fluids appear white but darker than the fluid signal in T2 images, and Fats appear bright but slightly darker than the fat signal in T 1 images (Figure 1.24).

