\section*{The Facial Bones}

The facial bones underlie the facial structures and supports the soft tissues of the face, enclose the eyeballs, form the nasal and oral cavities, and support the teeth of the upper and lower jaws.
There are 14 facial bones comprising the facial skeleton: (Figure 5.20)
- Maxilla (2)
- Palatine bones (2)
- Zygomatic bones (2)
- Nasal bones (2)
- Inferior nasal concha (2)
- Lacrimal bones (2)
- Vomer (1)
- Mandible (1)
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-132.jpg?height=760&width=940&top_left_y=877&top_left_x=330)

Figure 5.20 Anterior view of skull showing facial bones

Maxilla: it is pair of pyramidal shaped bones fused to form the upper jaw. Maxilla is composed of body and four projections (Figure 5.21):
- Frontal process
- Zygomatic process
- Alveolar process
- Palatine process
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-133.jpg?height=1099&width=606&top_left_y=576&top_left_x=376)

Figure 5.21 Anterior view of the skull (a) and lateral view of the skull (b) illustrating the Maxilla

Processes of Maxilla: the maxilla has three processes (Figure 5.22):
1. The Frontal process.
2. The Zygomatic process.
3. The Alveolar process.
4. The Palatine process.

The Frontal process: is a strong plate, projects upward, medially and backward, by the side of the nose, forming part of its lateral boundary.
The Zygomatic process: is a rough triangular eminence, which protrudes laterally creating a non-smooth articular surface with the zygomatic bone.
The Alveolar process: is the thickened ridge of bone that contains the tooth sockets (dental alveoli) on the jaw bones that hold teeth; it represents the upper jaw
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-134.jpg?height=524&width=697&top_left_y=777&top_left_x=447)

Figure 5.22 Processes of Maxilla

The Palatine process of maxilla: it is a thick, horizontal process of the maxilla. It forms the anterior three quarters of the hard palate (at the roof of the mouth), and the posterior one quarter of the hard palate is formed by the horizontal plate of the palatine bone (Figure 5.23).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-135.jpg?height=1172&width=617&top_left_y=544&top_left_x=377)

Figure 5.23 Sagittal (a) and inferior view (b) Illustrating the palatine and alveolar processes of Maxilla

Palatine Bone: it is one of a pair of bones forms the posterior portion of hard palate (the roof of the oral cavity) and is directly inferior to the nasal cavity (Figure 5.24).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-136.jpg?height=1173&width=572&top_left_y=480&top_left_x=516)

Figure 5.24 Sagittal (a) and inferior view (b) Illustrating the Palatine Bone

Zygomatic Bones: The two zygomatic bones are located in the upper and lateral parts of the face forming the lateral wall of the orbit. The zygomatic bone, also known as the cheek bone, supports the region of the face known as the cheek, protects organs in this area. The short temporal process of the zygomatic bone projects posteriorly, where it forms the anterior portion of the zygomatic arc (Figure 5.25).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-137.jpg?height=1138&width=803&top_left_y=540&top_left_x=250)

Figure 5.25 Anterior (a) and lateral (b) illustration of Zygomatic Bone

Nasal Bones: consists of two bones located near the middle of the face, they come together to form the nasal bridge of the nose. These bones vary in size from individual to individual. The main function of nasal bones is the support of the nose (Figure 5.26).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-138.jpg?height=567&width=540&top_left_y=472&top_left_x=551)

Figure 5.26 Nasal Bone

Nasal concha: plural conchae, it is a long, narrow, curled shelf of bone that protrudes into the nasal cavity, there are three nasal conchae, superior, middle and inferior.
The superior and middle nasal conchae form part of the ethmoid bone, while the inferior nasal concha is a bonystructure by itself Nasal conchae divide the nasal airway into 4 groove-like air passages, and are responsible for forcing inhaled air to flow in a steady, regular pattern around the largest possible surface area of nasal mucosa (Figure 5.27).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-138.jpg?height=392&width=938&top_left_y=1315&top_left_x=335)

Figure 5.27 Nasal conchae

Lacrimal Bone: The lacrimal bone (lacrima is Latin word means tear) is the smallest bone of the skull. It is paired and sits inside the bony orbit taking up a small area of the most anterior part of the medial wall (Figure 5.28). The lacrimal bone has two surfaces, a lateral (orbital) and medial (nasal) one.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-139.jpg?height=479&width=615&top_left_y=533&top_left_x=353)

Figure 5.28 Lacrimal Bone
Vomer: The Vomer is a singular bone that runs vertically within the nasal cavity, separating the left and right sides. The Vomer forms the posterior inferior aspect of the nasal septum posteroinferior to the perpendicular plate of the ethmoid bone (Figure 5.29).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-139.jpg?height=486&width=753&top_left_y=1175&top_left_x=286)

Figure 5.29 Vomer

The Mandible: This bone forms the lower jaw of the human skull; its main function is support of the lower part of the face and holding the bottom half of the teeth in place. The mandible is essential for movement of the mouth (Figure 5.30).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-140.jpg?height=563&width=538&top_left_y=474&top_left_x=550)

Figure 5.30 The Mandible

The mandible consists of following parts (Figure 5.31):
1. Body.
2. Ramus.
3. Angle.
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-140.jpg?height=375&width=724&top_left_y=1277&top_left_x=446)

Figure 5.31 Anatomical components of the Mandible

The body of the mandible: it is horseshoe shaped part of the mandible, lies anteriorly in horizontal direction; it is connected to the two rami posteriorly at the angle of the mandible.
The Ramus of the mandible: There are two mandibular rami, which project perpendicularly upwards from the angle of the mandible. Each ramus contains the following bony landmarks.
1. Coronoid process.
2. Head.
3. Neck.

The Angle of the mandible: it is located at the junction between the posterior part of the body and the lower part of the ramus of the mandible.

