\section*{Ribs and Costal cartilages}
ribs are long bones, flattened and curved. There are twelve pairs of ribs in the thoracic cage; they connect the sternum anteriorly to the upper ten thoracic vertebrae posteriorly.
Function of ribs: As part of the thoracic, the ribs protect the vital thoracic and part of the abdominal organs. They also play a role in breathing, as they move to permit lung inflation during thoracic expansion.
Rib Classifications: there are two types of rib classification:
1- According to their anatomical features ribs are classified into: Typical and Atypical ribs.
2- According to their articulation, location and their costal cartilage ribs are classified into: True, Floating and False ribs.
Typical Ribs include from $3^{\text {rd }}$ up to $\mathbf{9}^{\text {th }}$ ribs: A typical rib is mainly composed of: head, neck and body. The head of a typical rib is wedge shaped with two articular facets separated by crest, the inferior facet articulates with the numerically corresponding vertebrae and the superior facet articulates with the vertebrae above. The neck of a typical rib connects the head with the body at a roughed tubercle, with a facet for articulation with the transverse process of the corresponding vertebrae. The body of a typical rib is thin, flat and curved, most markedly at the costal angle where the rib turns anterolaterally; there is a groove in internal surface of the body of a typical rib for the protection of the neurovascular supply of the thorax (Figure 7.5).
