\section*{True, False and Floating ribs}

The first seven ribs (from $1^{\text {st }}$ down to $7^{\text {th }}$ ribs) are True ribs; the main feature of true ribs is that the costal cartilages from these ribs are directly attached to the sternum. The next lower five ribs (from $8^{\text {th }}$ down to $12^{\text {th }}$ ribs) are False ribs, the main feature of false ribs is that the costal cartilages from these ribs do not directly attach to the sternum. The costal cartilages from $8^{\text {th }}, 9^{\text {th }}$ and $10^{\text {th }}$ ribs are attached to the cartilage of the next higher ribs. The two lower ribs ( $11^{\text {th }}$ and $12^{\text {th }}$ ribs) are Floating ribs the main feature of these ribs is that they are short and do not attach to the sternum at all. The costal cartilages of these ribs terminate within the musculature of the lateral abdominal wall (Figure 7.9).
![](https://cdn.mathpix.com/cropped/2025_04_09_5c7058303e6d1c6ad4cfg-165.jpg?height=733&width=898&top_left_y=704&top_left_x=222)

Figure 7.9 Classification of Ribs into True, False and Floating
The costal cartilages: There are 12 pairs of costal cartilage form part of the anterior wall of the thoracic cage. They connect the ribs to the sternum and help in extending the forward motion of the ribs. They also contribute to thoracic elasticity within by allowing chest expand during respiration. The upper seven pairs of costal cartilage are directly connected to the sternum, while the next lower three pairs are connected with the next upper ribs, and the last two pairs of costal cartilage are pointed, ending in the abdominal wall.

