\section*{Metacarpophalangeal joint}

Metacarpophalangeal joints are condyloid type synovial joints between the head of metacarpal and the base of proximal phalanx in each of the 5 digits. Each joint is enclosed by a fibrous capsule which attaches to the margins of the articular surfaces and is lined by a synovial membrane. There are two collateral ligaments and one palmar ligament associated with each metacarpophalangeal joint.

\section*{Interphalangeal joints}

Interphalangeal joints are hinge joints between the phalanges, there are two Interphalangeal joints in each digit except the thumb which has only one interphalangeal joint. The two joints are: Proximal Interphalangeal Joints between the proximal phalanx and intermediate phalanx in each of the 2nd to 5th digits and Distal Interphalangeal Joints between the intermediate phalanx and distal phalanx in each of the 2 nd to 5 th digits (Figure 10.13).
