\section*{The Femur}

The femur is the bone of the thigh and the longest bone in the body, it can be divided into three regions; proximal region, shaft and distal region.
The Proximal region of the femur:
The proximal aspect of the femur consists of a head and neck, the greater and lesser trochanters, with two bony ridges connecting the two trochanters; the intertrochanteric line anteriorly and the trochanteric crest posteriorly.
The Head of the femur is the rounded, proximal end of the femur, it has a smooth surface and covered with articular cartilage, it articulates with the acetabulum of the hip bone to form the hip joint
The Neck of the femur is the cylindrical narrowed region below the head; it connects the head of the femur with the shaft. It is set at an angle of approximately 135 degrees to the shaft. This angle of projection allows for an increased range of movement at the hip joint. The Greater trochanter is an upward, bony projection extending from the base of the neck, it is the most palpable bony projection on the lateral side of the upper thigh.
The Lesser trochanter is a small, bony projection extending from the posteromedial aspect of the inferior part of the neck of the femur.
The Intertrochanteric line is a bony ridge extends between the two trochanters in an inferomedial direction on the anterior surface of the femur. It serves as the anterior attachment of the hip joint capsule.
The Intertrochanteric crest is a bony ridge located on the posterior surface of the femur, it connects the two trochanters (Figure 12.2).

\section*{The Shaft of the femur:}

The shaft of the femur is cylindrical in the middle with posterior flattening and widening in the proximal and distal ends, as it descends the femoral shaft has a slight medial bowing, which brings the knees closer to the body's centre of gravity, increasing stability. The linea aspera (Latin for rough line) are roughened ridges on the posterior surface of the shaft of the femur, they are made up of medial and lateral lips, the medial lip originates near the lesser trochanter as the pectineal line, and the lateral lip arises from the greater trochanter as the gluteal tuberosity, the two ridges split inferiorly to form the medial and lateral supracondylar lines, the popliteal surface is a triangular space lies between these two lines (Figure 12.2).

\section*{The Distal region of the femur:}

The distal region of the femur, which articulates with the tibia and patella at the knee joint, is made up of the medial and lateral condyles, the intercondylar fossa, and the patellar surface.
The Medial and Lateral condyles: are rounded areas at the end of the femur, they articulate with the tibia and menisci of the knee on the posterior and inferior surfaces, while they articulate with the patella on the anterior surface. The lateral condyle is larger and more prominent than the medial condyle; the prominence of the lateral condyle
prevents the lateral dislocation of the patella, while the flatter and smaller medial condyle may result in medial dislocation of the patella. The medial and lateral condyles are connected anteriorly, while they are separated posteriorly by the Intercondylar fossa. The medial wall of the intercondylar fossa serve as the point of attachment for the anterior cruciate ligament (ACL), while the lateral wall of the intercondylar fossa serve as the point of attachment for the posterior cruciate ligament (PCL).
The Medial and lateral epicondyles: are bony elevations on the outer sides of the condyles, they provide attachment for muscles and supporting ligaments of the knee joint. The medial epicondyle: is located on the outer medial side of the medial condyle, while the lateral epicondyle is located on the outer lateral side of the lateral condyle. The medial epicondyle is the larger than the lateral epicondyle, there is a small bony prominence at the superior margin of the medial epicondyle known as the adductor tubercle (Figure 12.3).
