\section*{The Metatarsal bones:}

The Metatarsal bones are group of five long bones connect the tarsals to the phalanges; they are of convex in shape with an upward arch, which give the foot its characteristic arch, which is essential in weight bearing and walking. They are numbered from the medial side of the foot as the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth metatarsals. Each metatarsal bone articulates proximally with one or more of the tarsal bones at the tarsometatarsal joints, and they articulate distally with proximal phalanges at the metatarsophalangeal joints. They also articulate at their bases with each other at the intermetatarsal joints as follows:
- The first metatarsal articulates with the medial cuneiform, and to a small extent to the intermediate cuneiform.
- The second metatarsal articulates with the three cuneiforms.
- The third metatarsal articulates with the lateral cuneiform.
- The fourth metatarsal articulates with the lateral cuneiform and the cuboid.
- The fifth metatarsal articulates with the cuboid (Figures 12.9 \& 12.14).

\section*{The Phalanges:}

The Phalanges of the foot are the bones of the toes, they are fourteen bones, each toe has three phalanges, proximal, intermediate and distal except the big toe, which only has two phalanges.
